'''''UFC 239: Jones vs. Santos''''' was a [[mixed martial arts]] event produced by the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] that was held on July 6, 2019, at [[T-Mobile Arena]] in [[Paradise, Nevada]], part of the [[Las Vegas–Paradise, NV MSA|Las Vegas Metropolitan Area]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/3/3/18248174/ufc-announces-dates-for-second-quarter-of-2019|title=UFC announces dates for second quarter of 2019|date=2019-03-03|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Newswire|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmadna.nl/de-ufc-kondigt-drie-nieuwe-locaties-aan-voor-evenementen-in-mei-en-juni-2019/|title=The UFC announces three new locations for events in May and June 2019|publisher=mmadna.nl|author=Marcel Dorff|date=3 March 2019 |access-date=2019-03-04}} {{in lang|nl}}</ref>

==Background==
A [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship]] bout between current two-time champion [[Jon Jones]] and [[Thiago Santos]] served as the event headliner.<ref name="twotitles">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mma/ufc/story/_/id/26374996/jones-santos-nunes-holm-headline-ufc-239|title=Jones-Santos, Nunes-Holm to headline UFC 239|author=Brett Okamoto|work=espn.com|date=2019-03-27|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>

A [[UFC Women's Bantamweight Championship]] bout between the current champion [[Amanda Nunes]] (also current [[UFC Women's Featherweight Championship|UFC Women's Featherweight Champion]]) and former champion [[Holly Holm]] served as the event co-headliner.<ref name="twotitles" />

A bout between former UFC Heavyweight title challenger [[Francis Ngannou]] and former [[UFC Heavyweight Championship|UFC Heavyweight Champion]] [[Junior dos Santos]] was scheduled to take place at this event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/3/29/18287780/francis-ngannou-vs-junior-dos-santos-slated-for-ufc-239|title=Francis Ngannou vs. Junior dos Santos slated for UFC 239|date=2019-03-29|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Jose Youngs|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> The matchup was originally scheduled to take place in September 2017 at [[UFC 215]], but dos Santos pulled out of that event, citing a failed drug test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmajunkie.com/2017/08/junior-dos-santos-potential-doping-violation-pulled-ufc-215|title=Junior Dos Santos notified of potential doping violation, pulled from UFC 215|date=2017-08-18|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=John Morgan|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> However, it was reported on  May 21, that the bout was being moved to headline [[UFC on ESPN 3]] after former [[UFC Welterweight Championship|UFC Welterweight Champion]] [[Tyron Woodley]] was forced to pull out of his rematch against also former champion [[Robbie Lawler]] due to a hand injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/26794549/dos-santos-ngannou-moved-june-29|title=Sources: dos Santos-Ngannou moved to June 29|date=2019-05-21|work=espn.com|author=Brett Okamoto|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>

A featherweight bout between former [[List of Strikeforce champions|Strikeforce]] and [[List of WEC champions#Lightweight Championship|WEC Lightweight Champion]] (as well as former [[UFC Lightweight Championship]] challenger) [[Gilbert Melendez]] and [[Arnold Allen]] headlined the prelims of the event.<ref name="MelendezAllen">{{cite web|url=https://www.mmanews.com/former-title-contender-gilbert-melendez-returns-at-ufc-239-in-july/|title=Former title contender Gilbert Melendez returns at UFC 239 in July|publisher=mmanews.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2019-05-08|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> The matchup was originally scheduled to take place in November 2018 at [[The Ultimate Fighter: Heavy Hitters#The Ultimate Fighter 28 Finale|The Ultimate Fighter: Heavy Hitters Finale]], however Melendez pulled out of the fight citing an injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/11/5/18065158/rick-glenn-steps-in-for-injured-gilbert-melendez-fights-arnold-allen-at-tuf-28-finale|title=Rick Glenn steps in for injured Gilbert Melendez, fights Arnold Allen at TUF 28 Finale|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Alexander K. Lee|date=2018-11-05|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>

A bantamweight bout between [[The Ultimate Fighter: Latin America]] bantamweight winner [[Alejandro Pérez (fighter)|Alejandro Pérez]] and [[Song Yadong]] took place at this event.<ref name="PerezSong">{{Cite web|url=https://mmadna.nl/tweede-poging-voor-alejandro-perez-vs-song-yadong-tijdens-ufc-239-in-las-vegas/|title=Second attempt for Alejandro Perez vs. Song Yadong during UFC 239 in Las Vegas|date=2019-05-14|publisher=mmadna.nl|author=Marcel Dorff|access-date=2019-05-14}} {{in lang|nl}}</ref> The matchup was originally scheduled to take place in March 2019 at [[UFC 235]], but Song pulled out of the fight for undisclosed reasons.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://mymmanews.com/cody-stamann-alejandro-perez-ufc-235/|title=Cody Stamann: 'I'm going to beat the s—t out of' Alejandro Perez|publisher=mymmanews.com|author=Mike Heck|date=2019-02-10|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref>

[[Sean O'Malley (fighter)|Sean O'Malley]] was expected to face [[Marlon Vera]] at the event. However, O'Malley announced his withdrawal from the bout on June 21 due a failed test for [[Enobosarm|ostarine]]. The Nevada State Athletic Commission decided to suspend him due to the failed test, however the United States Anti Doping Association [[USADA]] did not impose any further sanctions.  The [[Enobosarm|ostarine]] in his system was likely residual from his previously failed test prior to [[UFC 229]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Alexander Lee|title=Sean O'Malley announces withdrawal from UFC 239 after banned substances 'resurfaced' |url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/6/21/18701636/sean-omalley-announces-withdrawal-from-ufc-239-after-banned-substances-resurfaced |publisher=mmafighting.com|date=2019-06-21|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref> Drako Rodriguez from [[King of the Cage]] was offered to replaced O'Malley initially; however the president of the promotion, Terry Trebilcock, refused to release him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/7/2/20677891/manager-rips-regional-promotion-for-not-allowing-fighter-out-of-contract-to-fight-in-the-ufc|title=Manager rips regional promotion for not allowing fighter out of contract to fight in the UFC|last=Martin|first=Damon|date=2019-07-02|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> Nohelin Hernandez served as the replacement.<ref name="O'Malley">{{Cite web|url=http://mmadna.nl/nohelin-hernandez-pakt-zeer-short-notice-partij-tegen-marlon-vera-aankomende-zaterdag/|title=Nohelin Hernandez takes very short notice against Marlon Vera next Saturday|author=Staff|publisher=mmadna.nl|date=2019-07-02|access-date=2019-07-02}} {{in lang|nl}}</ref>

[[Melissa Gatto]] was scheduled to face [[Julia Avila]] at the event. However, Gatto was removed from the card on June 24 for undisclosed reasons and was replaced by returning veteran [[Pannie Kianzad]].<ref name="GattoOut">{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/06/melissa-gatto-out-pannie-kianzad-returns-vs-julia-avila-ufc-239|title=UFC 239: With Melissa Gatto out, Pannie Kianzad returns to take on Julia Avila|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Nolan King and Mike Bohn|date=2019-06-24|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>

UFC 239 served as the first UFC to air on PPV in the United Kingdom. Following this event select UFC numbered events will now air on [[BT Sport Box Office]] in the United Kingdom.

